# Heartbeat monitor (shared, non-negotiable)

Full protocol + script live in brain-box:

- Script: `/Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/meta/tools/monitor_compute_jobs.py`
- Doc: `/Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/agents/heartbeat-monitor.md`
- Canonical rule: `/Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/.cursor/rules/heartbeat-monitor.mdc`

**Default: wire the monitor.** If you background a compute job in this
repo (walk-forward eval, live signal loop soak, agent stress-test, etc.)
and don't attach a monitor, state the justification inline in the
assistant message. Silence is not acceptable. After wiring, wait one
sampling interval (~30–60 s) and read the tail of the heartbeat log to
confirm at least one healthy sample landed before ending your turn.

## When to wire it in

Any compute job that satisfies **any** of:

- Wall-clock estimate ≥ **10 minutes**.
- Emits **no stdout** for most of the run (per-bar replays, DRL rollouts,
  training loops, batch dispatchers, LLM eval sweeps).
- Runs in the **background** (`block_until_ms: 0` in Cursor `Shell`,
  `nohup … &`, or a launched daemon).
- Blocks a downstream verdict / gate / decision the user is waiting on.

## Standard invocation

```bash
python3 /Users/the1finix/Documents/GitHub/brain-box/meta/tools/monitor_compute_jobs.py \
    --pid $JOB_PID:$LABEL \
    --output-artefact $JOB_PID:$OUTPUT_PATH \
    --tail-on-exit $JOB_PID:$STDOUT_LOG_PATH:200 \
    --notify \
    --interval 30 --cpu-floor 20 --stall-samples 4 \
    --jsonl ./reviews/compute_heartbeat.jsonl \
    --log   ./reviews/compute_heartbeat.log
```

Background it (`block_until_ms: 0`) in the same shell-call batch as the
compute job. Reserve `--notify` for cases where the user is likely to
be away for > 15 min.

## Why not maintain a local copy

Two workspaces (`finance-research-experiments`, `multi-pair-trading-agent`)
each lost 40+ minutes of compute to preventable stalls. Rather than
teach every workspace agent this lesson separately, brain-box owns the
canonical script and doc, and every workspace pulls the same protocol
via this rule.

If you patch behaviour, patch the brain-box version — do not fork.
